<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-05-12T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-05-12T06:00:00-05:00" n="197" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d197">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/163: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-05-12T19:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">May 12,
                                        1927—7 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 12—8:55
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>547. Following from American consul at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“May 11, 8 p.m. A considerable number of American mission
                                    buildings in Nanking are still occupied as barracks, and one
                                    church is being used as a military hospital.”</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>